{"title_page": "Criticize (song)", "text_new": "{{short description|1987 single by Alexander O'Neal}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Criticize\n| cover      = Criticize.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = U.S. cover art\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Alexander O'Neal]]\n| album      = [[Hearsay (album)|Hearsay]]\n| B-side     = \"A Broken Heart Can Mend\" / \"Fake (Extended Version)\" (UK 12\" only)\n| released   = {{start date|September 23, 1987}}\n| format     = {{flatlist|\n* [[gramophone record|7\"]]\n* [[12-inch single|12\"]]\n}}\n| recorded   = 1987\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 4:09 <small>(album version)</small><br>4:00 <small>(single version)</small>\n| label      = [[Tabu Records|Tabu]]\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n* Alexander O'Neal\n* [[Jellybean Johnson|Garry Johnson]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Jellybean Johnson]]\n* [[Jimmy Jam & Terry Lewis]]\n}}\n| chronology = [[Alexander O'Neal]]\n| prev_title = [[Fake (Alexander O'Neal song)|Fake]]\n| prev_year  = 1987\n| next_title = [[Never Knew Love Like This]]\n| next_year  = 1988\n| misc       = \n}}\n\"'''Criticize'''\"  is a song written by [[Alexander O'Neal]] and [[Jellybean Johnson]] and recorded by American recording artist [[Alexander O'Neal]]. It was the second single from O'Neal's second solo album, ''[[Hearsay (album)|Hearsay]]'' (1987). The song's distinctive backing vocals were performed by [[Lisa Keith]]. Following the successful chart performances of the ''[[Hearsay (album)|Hearsay]]'' single \"[[Fake (Alexander O'Neal song)|Fake]]\", \"Criticize\" was released as the album's second single.\n\n==Meaning==\nThe song's lyrics are a personal commentary, critical of a nagging ex-lover, who criticizes his \"friends\", \"ideals\", \"lifestyle\", and \"feeling[s]\".\n\n==Release==\nThe song peaked at No. 4 on the [[UK Singles Chart]], becoming his biggest hit in that region. In O'Neal's native United States, it peaked at No. 4 on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|R&B chart]], and No. 70 on the main [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. It was also one of his only two hits to chart in the [[Ireland Singles Chart|Republic of Ireland]] (reaching No. 14).\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe song is featured in the soundtrack of the video game ''[[The Vibe 98.8|Grand Theft Auto IV]]'' on the in-game radio station \"[[Grand Theft Auto IV soundtrack|The Vibe 98.8]]\".\n\n==Track listing==\n* '''12\" Maxi (Tabu TBU 651158 6)'''\n# \"Criticize (Remix)\" - 7:00\n# \"Criticize (Edit)\" - 3:55\n# \"Criticize (A Cappella)\" - 2:40\n# \"Criticize (Critical Mix)\" - 5:30\n# \"Criticize (Critical Edit)\" - 3:45\n# \"Criticize (Critical Dub)\" - 4:30\n# \"Criticize (Nag Mix)\" - 1:35\n\n* '''12\" Single'''\n# \"Criticize (Remix)\" - 7:00\n# \"Criticize (Critical Mix)\" - 5:30\n# \"Fake (Extended Version)\" - 5:20\n\n* '''7\" Single (Tabu 651158 7)'''\n# \"Criticize\" - 4:00\n# \"A Broken Heart Can Mend\" - 3:40\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from the album's liner notes.<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite book|title=Hearsay ''liner notes''|year=1987|publisher=[[Tabu Records]]}}</ref>\n* [[Alexander O'Neal]] - lead vocals\n* [[Jellybean Johnson]] - drum and keyboard programming, keyboards, guitar, drums, percussion\n* Jimmy Jam - drum and synth programming, keyboards\n* [[Lisa Keith]] - backing vocals\n* Brie Darling - Drums\n\n==Sales chart performance==\n===Peak positions===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Chart (1987)\n!Position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|14|song=Criticize|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|17|year=1987|week=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|40|artist=Alexander O'Neal|song=Criticize|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|4|artist=Alexander O'Neal|song=Criticize|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|70|artist=Alexander O'Neal|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboarddanceclubplay|21|artist=Alexander O'Neal|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|4|artist=Alexander O'Neal|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|West Germany|24|artist=Alexander O'Neal|song=Criticize|songid=31200|accessdate=February 25, 2019}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|alexander-o'neal|criticize}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Hearsay (album)}}\n{{Alexander O'Neal}}\n\n[[Category:1987 singles]]\n[[Category:Alexander O'Neal songs]]\n[[Category:1987 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]\n\n\n{{1980s-R&B-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1987 single by Alexander O'Neal}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Criticize\n| cover      = Criticize.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = U.S. cover art\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Alexander O'Neal]]\n| album      = [[Hearsay (album)|Hearsay]]\n| B-side     = \"A Broken Heart Can Mend\" / \"Fake (Extended Version)\" (UK 12\" only)\n| released   = {{start date|September 23, 1987}}\n| format     = {{flatlist|\n* [[gramophone record|7\"]]\n* [[12-inch single|12\"]]\n}}\n| recorded   = 1987\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 4:09 <small>(album version)</small><br>4:00 <small>(single version)</small>\n| label      = [[Tabu Records|Tabu]]\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n* Alexander O'Neal\n* [[Jellybean Johnson|Garry Johnson]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Jellybean Johnson]]\n* [[Jimmy Jam & Terry Lewis]]\n}}\n| chronology = [[Alexander O'Neal]]\n| prev_title = [[Fake (Alexander O'Neal song)|Fake]]\n| prev_year  = 1987\n| next_title = [[Never Knew Love Like This]]\n| next_year  = 1988\n| misc       = \n}}\n\"'''Criticize'''\"  is a song written by [[Alexander O'Neal]] and [[Jellybean Johnson]] and recorded by American recording artist [[Alexander O'Neal]]. It was the second single from O'Neal's second solo album, ''[[Hearsay (album)|Hearsay]]'' (1987). The song's distinctive backing vocals were performed by [[Lisa Keith]]. Following the successful chart performances of the ''[[Hearsay (album)|Hearsay]]'' single \"[[Fake (Alexander O'Neal song)|Fake]]\", \"Criticize\" was released as the album's second single.\n\n==Meaning==\nThe songs lyrics are a personal commentary, critical of a nagging ex-lover, who criticizes his \"friends\", \"ideals\", \"lifestyle\", and \"feeling[s]\".\n\n==Release==\nThe song peaked at No. 4 on the [[UK Singles Chart]], becoming his biggest hit in that region. In O'Neal's native United States, it peaked at No. 4 on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|R&B chart]], and No. 70 on the main [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. It was also one of his only two hits to chart in the [[Ireland Singles Chart|Republic of Ireland]] (reaching No. 14).\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe song is featured in the soundtrack of the video game ''[[The Vibe 98.8|Grand Theft Auto IV]]'' on the in-game radio station \"[[Grand Theft Auto IV soundtrack|The Vibe 98.8]]\".\n\n==Track listing==\n* '''12\" Maxi (Tabu TBU 651158 6)'''\n# \"Criticize (Remix)\" - 7:00\n# \"Criticize (Edit)\" - 3:55\n# \"Criticize (A Cappella)\" - 2:40\n# \"Criticize (Critical Mix)\" - 5:30\n# \"Criticize (Critical Edit)\" - 3:45\n# \"Criticize (Critical Dub)\" - 4:30\n# \"Criticize (Nag Mix)\" - 1:35\n\n* '''12\" Single'''\n# \"Criticize (Remix)\" - 7:00\n# \"Criticize (Critical Mix)\" - 5:30\n# \"Fake (Extended Version)\" - 5:20\n\n* '''7\" Single (Tabu 651158 7)'''\n# \"Criticize\" - 4:00\n# \"A Broken Heart Can Mend\" - 3:40\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from the album's liner notes.<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite book|title=Hearsay ''liner notes''|year=1987|publisher=[[Tabu Records]]}}</ref>\n* [[Alexander O'Neal]] - lead vocals\n* [[Jellybean Johnson]] - drum and keyboard programming, keyboards, guitar, drums, percussion\n* Jimmy Jam - drum and synth programming, keyboards\n* [[Lisa Keith]] - backing vocals\n* Brie Darling - Drums\n\n==Sales chart performance==\n===Peak positions===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Chart (1987)\n!Position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|14|song=Criticize|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|17|year=1987|week=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|40|artist=Alexander O'Neal|song=Criticize|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|4|artist=Alexander O'Neal|song=Criticize|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|70|artist=Alexander O'Neal|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboarddanceclubplay|21|artist=Alexander O'Neal|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|4|artist=Alexander O'Neal|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|West Germany|24|artist=Alexander O'Neal|song=Criticize|songid=31200|accessdate=February 25, 2019}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|alexander-o'neal|criticize}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Hearsay (album)}}\n{{Alexander O'Neal}}\n\n[[Category:1987 singles]]\n[[Category:Alexander O'Neal songs]]\n[[Category:1987 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]\n\n\n{{1980s-R&B-song-stub}}\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMeaning:Typo fixing, replaced: songs lyrics \u2192 song's lyrics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Criticize_(song)"}
